This RET site project has led to the

(1) Training of 35 participating teachers who gained knowledge in CS concepts, principles and research topics, developed CS lessons from the research, introduced the CS lessons to their schools, and shared the lesson materials to over 120 of their fellow teachers; 

(2) Publication of 35 lesson plans and lesson activities on thehttp://www.teachengineering.org/ Web Site, as well as 7 Journal papers, 5 conference proceedings papers, and 3 workshop presentations generated from the research projects and instructional practices; 

(3) Establishment of a local ACM CSTA chapter in the Metropolitan Omaha region with the RET Site participants serving as founding members and chapter officers;

(4) Proposal of a Master of Science degree program in Computer Science Education at the University of Nebraska at Omaha under the strong support of the RET site participants (Funding for the program was secured from the Online World Wide office of the University of Nebraska system for developing a sequence of online courses for the degree program.  One tenure-track faculty position has been allocated and recruited for this degree program.); and 

(5) Promotion of more 9-12 grade students participating in CS educational activities. For example, teams participating in our Annual High School CS Quiz Bowl and Programming Contests, held during the CS Education Week each year,  have grown from 12 in year 2012 to 24 in year 2015, with the RET Site participants serving as coaches of these teams mostly.



